________________________________________________


password + salt → hash
salt- random value added before hashing 

 without the salt ->  YES — same password → same hash every time hash("password")

with salt - bycrypt value 
bcrypt.hashpwd("password",salt)
$2b$12$K9u7...abc123hashedvalue  -> contains Algorithm ($2b), cost factor (12), salt($K9u7),hash 

During login

When user types password again:

System takes stored hash
Extracts the salt from it
Hashes the entered password using same salt
Compares result

Encryption = reversible (you can decrypt)
Hashing = irreversible (you can’t get original back)


________________________________________________

"FAST" = BAD -> For passwords, you actually want : Slow hashing as Attackers try millions of guesses/sec -> Slower hash = harder to crack


❌ MD5 Message Digest (insecure) -> Output: 128-bit hash , fast - easy brute force , rainbow table attacks, collision exists (sme psswd- sme hash)
❌ SHA-1 Secure Hash Algorithm (insecure) ->Output: 160-bit hash, Still too fast → brute-force , Collision attacks proven (e.g., SHAttered attack)

✅ bcrypt (recommended)  - slow + secure ->  has salt, modify cost factor(work factor) ,use blow fish cipher internally ,adaptive (inc. diff.)
bcrypt.hashpw(password,bcrypt.gensalt(rounds=12))  rounds=12 → controls how slow it is
Limiy- psswrd length (72 bytes),Not memory-hard (less resistant to GPU attacks than argon2)

✅ argon2 (very strong) - Memory-hard (uses RAM + CPU) , configurable - memory,time cost & parallelism , built in salt
Adv- ✔ Very hard for GPU attacks, Slows down attackers massively, Highly configurable
```
from argon2 import PasswordHasher
ph = PasswordHasher()
hash = ph.hash("password123")
ph.verify(hash, "password123")
```

Limits - More complex to configure

✅ PBKDF2 Password Based Key Function Derivation (also used) -> repeated hashing (usses iteration eg 100000 times),Works with SHA-256 typically,has built in salt
```
import hashlib
hashlib.pbkdf2_hac(
      'SHA256',
      b'password',
      b'salt',
      10000
)
```
limits - Not memory-hard, Less secure than argon2 for modern attacks

Django → uses PBKDF2 by default (can switch to Argon2)
FastAPI → commonly uses bcrypt/argon2 via passlib


